These water bodies served as liquid highways!  \n\nThere certainly were plenty of cypress trees around to use as building material.  The cypress wood was impervious to insects and rot, as evidenced by this canoe which is over 700 years old! Our community buries these sentiments so deeply, yet we forget that we stand on the shoulders of hundreds of thousands of fallen black Americans. Our ability to move to America to create opportunities for our people, our children, and our grandchildren is because of Black America. It is our time to have these heavy conversations with our families and our peers. Not racist is not good enough- we need to be anti-racist. I implore you all to watch Hasan’s entire video as he succinctly describes what our South Asian community is doing wrong. We need to stand for our Black countrymen and women, because without them, we wouldn’t be here. Let’s do our part. How do we do our part? Well, start by watching this video! At the end, Hasan includes many actionable items we can easily accomplish. Next, educate and donate! Here are some resources I have found incredibly useful in learning how to take meaningful action and educating yourself: Link Tree to numerous national resources including bail funds, mutual aid funds, donation links, mental health resources, trans funds (I do not know who created this, but will give credit when I figure it out!): https://linktr.ee/NationalResourcesList A consolidated list of petition links, email templates for your local legislators, donation fund links, educational links: https://blacklivesmatters.carrd.co/ BLM conversation translations for MANY South Asian languages (bring Ammama into the conversation!): https://docs.google.com/document/u/2/d/1qwon6Q-h3YC2n_vZGKIVxZxEhXG8ZQah4IVCMQzGaUk/mobilebasic How to bring up BLM in the South Asian community: http://theaerogram.com/revolution-starts-thathi-strategies-south-asians-bring-blacklivesmatter-home/ Standing in solidarity with Black Lives; addressing SA complicity (notice how it is written in 2015 and not this week!): https://queersouthasian.wordpress.com/ Black Lives Matter reading list: https://www.harpersbazaar.com/uk/culture/culture-news/g32731117/black-lives-matter-reading-list/ A list of Black-owned restaurants in the Greater Boston area (Petsi Pies has the BEST apple pies): https://www.boston.com/food/restaurants/2020/06/02/black-owned-restaurants-in-boston Watch 13th on Netflix to learn about the disproportionate criminalization of Black people in America: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=krfcq5pF8u8 Truthfully, you can Google many more resources if you feel this isn’t enough. I am more than happy to provide more and discuss with those willing to have an open and productive 05:42:32","pageCategory":"HINDU_TEMPLE","verified":false},"languageCode":"en","legacyId":0,"id":"15331361|3138483399542002"},{"platformId":"1470762849886760_2455132954783073","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-06-12 15:08:06","updated":"2021-06-20 17:13:43","type":"photo","message":"“I was frustrated, angry and sad” BY ANISHA PATEL It was January 26, 2020 and I was at the Atlanta airport picking up my husband, who had finally made it here from England after four years of dating and one year after our court marriage. Planning our Hindu wedding, scheduled to take place in four months, would be easier now that we no longer had to account for the five-hour time difference! The caveat – the wedding was to take place in England. It was not until early March that COVID-19 became a hot topic and we did not understand the severity of it at first, or realize the impact that it would have on our lives. We brushed it off saying, “This won’t affect travel and our wedding will still proceed as scheduled. We have nothing to worry about!” However, exactly one month before our wedding, it was announced that international travel was banned and large gatherings were prohibited. Wearing masks became a daily ritual. Months of planning and anticipation were stripped away from us just like that! The impact did not end there. Exactly two weeks prior to what would have been our wedding day, just as we were about to sign the paperwork for our first home, I received the news that I had been laid-off from my job as a physician assistant. A job that I loved, and had been doing for one-and-a-half years. I wasn’t the only one affected. Many medical practices were experiencing financial hardship resulting in some pretty hard decisions. Who knew that the country could afford to lay off medical providers even during a pandemic! I had been told by many that as a physician assistant, I would always have a job anywhere I went but here I was, with no income and no job security. I kept applying to one job after another only to realize that most companies had put a freeze on hiring. I became restless and it felt like everything was at a standstill. That our lives were not moving forward. Emotions were flooding through me. I was frustrated, angry and sad. I felt as if my thoughts were consuming me, so I kept busy. I painted, and I worked on art projects. Things that I had always loved to do, but had never devoted any time to doing while working full time. I also learned to cook new recipes, which then immediately graced my husband’s Instagram page. These are the moments that I will always cherish. As for our Hindu wedding, given the current uncertainty, we are not sure when or even if we will reschedule it. However, what I do know is that we are extremely blessed. We are blessed that my husband had immigrated here prior to the spread of COVID-19 and the subsequent indefinite ban on immigration. We are grateful that we are together. In the 1920s, immigration policies systematically barred and prevented immigration from non-white countries, completely excluding Asian countries to \"preserve the ideal of U.S. homogeneity.\" The civil rights movement and the Civil Rights Act of 1964 not only brought attention to the stark racial inequalities in the US but put a highlight on the racist and xenophobic immigration policies. As Hasan mentions, the Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965, also known as the Hart-Cellar Act, opened immigration to all Asian countries and naturalization rights to already in the US. This allowed many of our families to come to the United States in hopes of a better life. Our Desi communities exist and prevail due to the work of Black activists. This post does not exist to urge South Asians to care about the Black Lives Matter movement merely because of the ways Black activists have paved the way for our communities and families. Instead, it seeks to urge everyone to strengthen your will to support the movement, better understand our privilege and history, and motivate anyone reading to start this dialogue with your families. Challenge your inner dialogues and implicit biases. We should all work to educate ourselves and support in any way possible. This is simply one fraction of a larger conversation we must have to confront anti-blackness in our communities. We must promote and practice anti-racism.
